lign:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 2017\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| David Gale\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| ''Corner Store''\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Album\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Mastered by Jimmy Hotz\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 2019\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Albiter Sound\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| ''Motor''\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Album\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| -\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 2019\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Albiter Sound\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \"Hard Leave\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Single\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| -\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.jimmyhotz.com}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hotz, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American audio engineers]]\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Texas]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American session musicians]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from California]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:One-man bands]]\n[[Category:People from Sherman, Texas]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP primary sources|date=February 2008}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image = 1985-Jimmy Hotz.jpg \n| name = Jimmy Hotz\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Jimmy Hotz\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Sherman, Texas]] \n| genre = [[Art rock]], [[progressive rock]], [[blues]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[funk]], [[rhythm and blues|R&B]], [[contemporary Christian music]], [[Gospel music|gospel]]\n| occupation = [[Record producer|Producer]], [[engineer]], [[inventor]], [[musician]], [[recording engineer]], [[programmer]], [[author]], [[consultant]]\n| instrument = Vocals, [[guitar]], [[piano]], [[bass guitar]], the Hotz Box, the Hotz Translator, SpaceHarp, [[flute]]\n| associated_acts =\n| website  = {{URL|jimmyhotz.com}}\n| years_active = 1970\u2013present\n| label        = {{hlist|[[MCA Records|MCA]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]|[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]|[[Star Song Communications|Star Song]]|[[Warner Music Group|WEA]]|[[Cypress Records|Cypress]]|[[Frontiers Records|Frontiers]]| Dossier| Vision }}\n}}\n\n'''Jimmy Hotz''' is an American [[inventor]], [[record producer]], [[Audio engineering|recording engineer]], [[electronic music]] pioneer, audio expert, author and musician.\n\n== Background ==\nHotz began playing guitar at the age of seven.\n\nHe plays a number of instruments such as the guitar, keyboards, flute, drums and his own inventions such as the \"Hotz Box\" and the \"Hotz MIDI Translator\". Hotz has done a number of recordings where all of the instruments were played by him using only the Hotz Box as an input device.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv5n2/hotzmidi.html |title=THE HOTZ MIDI TRANSLATOR, Atari Team Redefines Electronic Instruments}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv3n9/hoytzsmidimagic.html |title=JIMMY HOTZ'S MIDI MAGIC}}</ref>\n\nIn the music business Jimmy Hotz has worked with [[Fleetwood Mac]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv3n1/makingtrackswithmidi.html |title=Making Tracks with MIDI: Mick Fleetwood}}</ref> [[Dave Mason]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv2n5/davemason.html |title=Making Tracks With MIDI: Rock Musician Dave Mason}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Dave-Mason-Two-Hearts/release/5671516 |title=Dave Mason - Two Hearts (Vinyl, LP, Album) at Discogs}}</ref> [[NSYNC]],<ref name=\"Moving To The Beat\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cgw.com/Publications/CGW/2001/Volume-24-Issue-11-November-2001-/Moving-to-the-Beat.aspx |title=Moving to the Beat}}</ref> Mobius 8 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cgw.com/publications/cgw/2001/volume-24-issue-11-november-2001-/moving-to-the-beat.aspx |title=Moving to the Beat}}</ref> [[B.B. King]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv3n9/hoytzsmidimagic.html |title=Jimmy Hotz's MIDI Magic.}}</ref> [[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[Jon Anderson]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8xF7i3xJDx4 |title=Atari Hotz Box History - Mick Fleetwood, Jon Anderson, Jimmy Hotz and others - YouTube}}</ref> Haven<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Er0haDX7Yfc |title=Haven - Celebrate}}</ref> and dozens of other recording artists as either a producer, engineer, mixer, studio musician, or musical instrument designer. Hotz was engineer and did programming on [[B.B. King]]'s Grammy-nominated ''King of the Blues: 1989''. Hotz was also the engineer on King's Grammy-nominated \"Standing on the Edge of Love\", for Best Contemporary Blues Recording in 1988 (from ''The Color of Money'' soundtrack).\n\n''You Rock Guitar'' featured a video of Jimmy playing their MIDI guitar through the Hotz Midi Translator software.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.yourockguitar.com/news//183-hotz-translator |title=You Rock Guitar and The Hotz MIDI Translator}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 he released his debut novel, ''The Gates of Time''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/gates-of-time-jimmy-hotz/1101122153 |title=The Gates of Time - Book}}</ref>\n\nHotz lived and worked in [[Southern California]] while developing his inventions.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.atarimagazines.com/startv3n9/hoytzsmidimagic.html |title = Jimmy Hotz's MIDI Magic}}</ref>\n\n==Inventions==\nHe is noted for his pioneering work with [[electronic music]] [[synthesizer]] [[MIDI]] controller development<ref>[http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv5n2/hotzmidi.html THE HOTZ MIDI TRANSLATOR]</ref> / programming and as a technical consultant to [[Microsoft]], [[Intel]], [[Electronic Arts]], [[Atari]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv5n2/hotzmidi.html |title=The Hotz MIDI Translator}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv3n10/newsnotesquotes.html |title=News, Notes & Quotes - Atari and Hotz Team Up!}}</ref> [[JBL (company)|JBL]] and other concerns for new product development.\n\nHe is the inventor of the \"Hotz Box\", Hotz \"MIDI vest\" and the \"Atari Hotz Box\", \"Hotz MIDI Translator\",<ref>[http://www.atarimagazines.com/startv3n9/hoytzsmidimagic.html JIMMY HOTZ'S MIDI MAGIC]</ref> computer software which has won interest and acclaim at the annual NAMM show. Performers such as Mick Fleetwood, Jon Anderson, Paul Haslinger, Scott Gershin and others have been using Hotz products in their creative work.<ref name=\"youtube.com\" />\n\nHe is the inventor of numerous electronic devices and software innovations and has received three US Patents<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents/about?id=ugYcAAAAEBAJ&ie=ISO-8859-1 |title=Patent for MIDI musical translator}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents?id=qlcdAAAAEBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jimmy+Hotz&hl=en&ei=on4YTsDsGtKcgQeXtsUB&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA |title=Electronic musical instrument for playing along with prerecorded music}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents?id=ZbgfAAAAEBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jimmy+Hotz&hl=en&ei=on4YTsDsGtKcgQeXtsUB&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAQ |title=Patent: Electronic musical instrument dynamically responding to varying chord and ..}}</ref> in music technology.\n\nAs an expert in 3D computer graphics, Hotz was the chief visionary behind the 3dMAxMedia \"Zuma Project\",<ref name=\"Moving To The Beat\" /> assembling the team which developed the technology to manipulate 3D imagery in real-time with audio, MIDI and other real-time control devices).\n\n\"Zuma\" won a 2001 Innovation award from Computer Graphics World Magazine and was used on the 2001 NSYNC [[PopOdyssey]] tour.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cgw.com/Publications/CGW/2001/Volume-24-Issue-12-December-2001-/Computer-Graphics-Worlds-2001-Innovation-Awards.aspx |title=Computer Graphics World's 2001 Innovation Awards}}</ref>\n\n==Patents==\n* US Patent No. 5,099,738: \"MIDI Musical Translator\"<ref>[http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&S1=5099738.PN.&OS=PN/5099738&RS=PN/5099738 US Patent No. 5,099,738], US Patent & Trademark Office, Patent Full Text and Image Database.</ref>\n* US Patent No. 5,502,274: \"Electronic musical instrument for playing along with prerecorded music and method of operation.\"<ref>[http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&d=PALL&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsrchnum.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&s1=5502274.PN.&OS=PN/5502274&RS=PN/5502274 US Patent No. 5,502,274], US Patent & Trademark Office, Patent Full Text and Image Database.</ref>\n* US Patent No. 5,619,003: \"Electronic musical instrument dynamically responding to varying chord and scale input information.\"<ref>[http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&d=PALL&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsrchnum.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&s1=5,619,003.PN.&OS=PN/5,619,003&RS=PN/5,619,003 US Patent No. 5,619,003], US Patent & Trademark Office, Patent Full Text and Image Database.</ref>\n* European Patent No. EP 0452347 B1: \"Universal Electronic Musical Instrument Controller\"<ref>[http://google.com/patents/EP0452347B1?cl=en European Patent No. EP 0452347 B1], Google Patents</ref>\n\n==Solo work==\nHe recorded a solo album, ''Beyond the Crystal Sea'', in the late 70s, which was released in 1980. It is listed as one of the Top 100 Christian Rock Albums of All Time, No. 98<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hmmagazine.com/blog/hm-exclusives/top-100-christian-rock-albums-of-all-time/ |title=Top 100 Christian Rock Albums of All Time}}</ref> and one of  CCM's 500 Best Albums Of All Time No. 210.<ref name=\"ccms500bestalbums.wordpress.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://ccms500bestalbums.wordpress.com/?s=hotz |title=CCM's 500 Best Albums of All Time, 210. Beyond the Crystal Sea \u2013 Jimmy Hotz}}</ref>\nIt is also considered one of, if not the best example of \"Christian Art Rock\" by critics and collectors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.angelicwarlord.com/reviews/h/jimmyhotz10.html |title=AngelicWarlord.com - Beyond the Crystal Sea \u2013 Jimmy Hotz}}</ref><ref>''Raised by Wolves: The Story of Christian Rock & Roll'' p.140 (Thompson 2000)</ref>\n\nHis music project, ''The Gates of Time'',<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/Jimmy-Hotz-The-Gates-Of-Time/release/4933379 |title = Jimmy Hotz - the Gates of Time}}</ref> was recorded using Hotz' invention, the Hotz Box along with the Hotz MIDI Translator software, which were the primary instruments.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== With various artists ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"vertical-align:top; text-align:left; width:40px;\"| Year\n! style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Artist\n! style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Recording\n! style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Type\n! style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Additional information\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 1976\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Dove\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \"Beyond the Blues\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Single\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 1978\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Silent Partner\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \"None the Wiser\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Single\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 1978\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Chuck Sugar\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| ''Master Key''\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Album\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 1978\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Various Artists\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| ''Dawntreader''\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Album\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| [[Star Song Communications]] release. Jimmy Hotz, ArkAngel, John Perez, Mark Christian and others.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 1979\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Randy Adams\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| ''Songs From Seven Years ''\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| Album\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\"| 1980\